      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Goodbye' Essay Evokes Memories of Farewells</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charlotte Kellar letter on Bob Lamm's August 13 Soapbox essay expresses sadness at not having had chance to say goodbye to favorite butcher (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>About a decade ago, there was a kosher butcher on Broadway in the high 80's. I noticed a special on lamb stew in the window and went in, only to find I had spent all my money. The butcher, who had never seen me before, said: ''Never mind. Take it and pay me tomorrow.''</p>
        <p>Henceforth, he was my butcher. We discussed culinary matters.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>About a decade ago, there was a kosher butcher on Broadway in the high 80's. I noticed a special on lamb stew in the window and went in, only to find I had spent all my money. The butcher, who had never seen me before, said: ''Never mind. Take it and pay me tomorrow.''</p>
        <p>Henceforth, he was my butcher. We discussed culinary matters.</p>
        <p>But one summer I visited my cousins in Copenhagen and when I returned, was shocked to find the entire building had been torn down. I wish I could have said goodbye.</p>
        <p>CHARLOTTE KELLAR  Upper West Side</p>
      </block>
